She is a bad ass, and almost NO ONE knows of her. She was a great ruler. She cared deeply for her people, and saw herself as their mother. She also shows no mercy to those who betrayed her or threatened her people as well.

She was disgusted by his actions, and challenged him to a duel. If he won, Persia would claim her people's land. If she won, the Persians must leave her people's land. She ended up winning the sword duel, and killed Cyrus the Great. The Persians left her lands as promised.

Her people were able to fend off the Persian attacks for the most part. However, her son was killed in combat by Cyrus if I recall. After hearing this news, she rushed to get her son's body. When Cyrus saw her, he fell in love with her and offered her to be one of his wives.

Her name is Tomyris of Scythia. She was the queen of some Massagetae tribes (who inhabited Central Asia during the time of Cyrus the Great) who were Indo-Iranian nomads. King Cyrus of Persia invaded her people's land in an effort to subjugate them.

So, to end this long post haha. My life rn is mostly stable. A few bumps in the road yes, but overall it's stable rn. I've grown to be stronger than I was in the past. Plus, I have friends who have taught me a lot. I know I'm still a WIP. However, I'm starting to love myself.

I am now a Chef's apprentice, I have started working out, and I hope to find another boyfriend sometime in the near future, but tbh rn I'm still dealing with things so I'm not exactly throwing myself out there just yet.

I started to embrace my true inner beliefs on things that for years I held to myself not to anger my family. I dropped out of college to pursue culinary arts. I didn't really have friends in college (as I wasn't an avid partier and was never invited). Now, I have friends.

I had a choice long ago to give up, and I didn't. I openly came out to my Dad last year, and some family found out (with mostly bad outcomes), I dated my first guy who I admit is a nice guy, and all around pleasant. We didn't last because of me.

A few of my friends who know my life story have told me I am strong. For the longest time I didn't believe it. I saw flaws in my character, and saw things that went wrong (that I initiated, or others did). However, tonight I realized, their insight was correct.

I have said things that have hurt my friends and those close to me, I have been silent when I should have spoken up, I have been forced to make drastic life changes due to events in my past. However, in the end I'm still alive.

My life has been a hectic mess of events up until this point haha. Still, it is currently somewhat hectic. Yet... it's stable at the same time. I have made a lot of mistakes in the past year, yet also some crucial strides towards a better life.
CW: Long Rant: I'll admit tonight on the way home from the gym I had some deep thoughts. They were about my life from childhood, till now at 21. A lot has happened in my life, good and bad.

That leads me to my final point. It's crucial for any non-ASD individual in a relationship (romantic, sexual, or friendships) with an ASD individual to do the following: be straightforward in almost everything (besides jokes), understand our natural phobia of extreme intimacy,

Due to our compulsive nature we may also at times obsess over helping some people if the AS individual is a compassionate person. That coupled with a lack of social etiquette leads to us at times overstepping others social boundaries when they come to us to vent/for advice.

This brings me to my final couple points. When you vent to people with Asperger's, you must understand that we will have a difficult time trying to help you. It doesn't mean we don't care about you, it's the exact opposite often.

We just don't typically understand the importance of these things, unless others point out their importance. This also means if you try and use body language to communicate with us we will likely not understand what you are doing.

On another note, people with an ASD may moderately or quite often ignore social etiquette, body language, and avoid eye contact. This makes some people feel disgusted, annoyed, and/or suspicious of us. We usually don't mean anyone else any harm, nor mean to cause discontent.

So in some situations that most people can tell require empathy we may accidentally ignore that and use sympathy. Which sometimes makes others think we are selfish and ignorant. In addition, we are very introspective people. Also often we are quite blunt haha.

With ASD individuals, we typically focus primarily on ourselves, and our understanding of the world around us. Thus, when it comes to understanding others, and trying to help others we always try doing so with the perspective we have.

Empathy is being able to imagine, feel, and understand someone else's experiences you have not yet experienced personally. Sympathy is being able to feel and understand another's experiences, because you have experienced them first-hand.

To start, people with ASD disorders typically have a hard time with feeling and using empathy. However, we still can experience some empathy, just not as strongly as the average person. Instead we are very sympathetic. The difference between the two is as follows:
